                                                                            <comments>
                            <comment id="74193" author="jamesanunez" created="Tue, 31 Dec 2013 18:24:17 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Landed in latest Lustre Documentation.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="71688" author="jamesanunez" created="Fri, 15 Nov 2013 21:35:52 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Proposed patch at: &lt;a href=&quot;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/8297/&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;http://review.whamcloud.com/#/c/8297/&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="71649" author="jamesanunez" created="Fri, 15 Nov 2013 18:25:41 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Jason, &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;There is room for confusion around the large_xattr/ea_inode feature. Right now, you can use &quot;large_xattr&quot; and &quot;ea_inode&quot; interchangeably in tune2fs and with mkfs.lustre, i.e. &quot;tune2fs -O large_xattr ...&quot; and &quot;tune2fs -O ea_inode&quot; produce the same result and the same is true for mkfs. In either case, you will see &quot;ea_inode&quot; in the filesystem features list with dumpe2fs. I just tested this with the latest 2.5.0 and 2.4.1. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If your experience differs from what I&apos;ve said above, please let me know what version of the code you are seeing this in and I will look into it. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;I know that there is a possibility that only large_xattr will be used in the future, but that has not happened yet. Thus, I agree that the documentation should be updated. I will post a patch to the documentation later today.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Thanks,&lt;br/&gt;
James&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;EDIT: What I should have said is, if your experience differs from what I outlined above, please let me know the version of e2fsprogs you are using. I used version 1.42.7.wc1. &lt;/p&gt;</comment>
